 in a planning context but also analyses a building's usage and ageing over its 'life cycle'. A system of criteria specially developed in an accompanying research project can be used to compare and evaluate buildings. It can also be used as a tool for optimising the sustainability of buildings in development during the planning process. By contrast, most existing sustainability systems are conceived not as design and planning tools, but as instruments for evaluating finished buildings and completed planning. 15 practical examples explain the ways in which these criteria and other aspects of sustainable building can be implemented in sophisticated architecture and how these can then be experienced. A system developed from analysing the examples is used to classify and compare the buildings. The building's significance as a lived environment is also not neglected here: sustainability develops in a dialogue between a building and its users, with an emphasis on residential usage.  aSustainability from the ground up - Building a home for the future  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aArchitecture -- Environmental aspects. 0aArchitecturexEnvironmental aspects. 0aSustainable architecture. 0aSustainable buildings -- Design and construction. 0aSustainable buildingsxDesign and construction. 4aArchitektur englisch. 4aNachhaltig Wohnen. 4aNachhaltige Architektur. 4aWohnkonzepte. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 aBraungart, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl khouli, Sebastian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGauzin-Müller, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilb, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGysin, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://i